>>57159881
The popculture obsession with AI comes and goes. There was a fad for it in the 60s and 70s, with Marvin Minsky claiming over fifty years ago that true strong AI with human-level intelligence or greater was less than two years away, and too many cookie-cutter dystopian sci-fi movies about "yeah but what if we create AI and it doesn't like us?"

https://archive.org/details/colossus-the-forbin-project-1970

Now we have AI evangelists from Le Plebbit saying that they've read Eliezer Yudkowsky's warnings about things that could go badly wrong if we created a true strong AI and connected it to complex and potentially dangerous machinery. But they all say "no, AI is gonna be amazing and fun! It'll be just like Star Trek! Nothing can go wrong! We're gonna end scarcity and poverty! We're gonna create God!" Said no one who's ever written one line of code, or can tell you the difference betwen an XOR gate and an OR gate.

I think AI is being vastly oversold right now, in terms of plausible near-future utility and capability. I also think general strong AI is either NP-complete or impossible even in principle. See also,

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halting_problem

I think a two things are at work here, in terms of this current obsession. I think part of it is escapism. Every sign points to people in the West generally and the US in particular being terrified of the future right now, for reasons ranging from economics to demography. When Americans are pessimistic and afraid they seek out cathartic horror movies and books--note the 20+ year obsession with a "zombie apocalypse"--and power fantasies. The power fantasies can be of throwing away all the rules and killing zombies, or of commanding godlike AI that can do everything for everybody. If I were a conspiracy theorist I would say that the AI obsession feels like a distraction from more important things.

But here. Catgirl.

VALIS. Mind you, if it hadn't had his name attached to it, it would never have been published. He thought it was a novel. The only way I could interpret it at all was to assume he was recounting a fever dream of amphetamine psychosis delusions and hallucinations, and he typed it all up on a battered prewar manual typewriter while tripping his balls off on acid at the end of a week-long speed bender.

But one of the ideas it touches on is that the viewpoint character, Horselover Fat, and the world in which he lives are caught in a time loop imposed by malevolent forces, and early 1970s Orange County, California and 1st Century Rome are somehow the same place, a "Black Iron Prison" that is somehow simultaneously a parallel timeline where the Antichrist is President, and in a tiny pocket universe. He keeps talking about the Dead Sea Scrolls in general and the Nag Hammadi Codex in particular. And there are benevolent aliens who crossed the galaxy to fix everything and want to help us because they're just that good, aliens who communicate with the viewpoint character by zapping information directly into his head with pink laser beams from an invisible alien satellite. It is even more incoherent than that sounds.

Dick was paranoid, severely clinically depressed, and seriously, heavily into drugs (which ones? all of them), most of his life. He was in and out of rehab until his love for amphetamines caused him to blow out a big blood vessel in his brain and die of a brain hemorrhage in 1982. He wrote some brilliant novels but this isn't one of them. The book has some moments of brilliant dialogue. And he had a profound, instinctive understanding of corruption and fear, that suffuse the whole thing. But there isn't really any kind of coherent story. No editor would have read more than the first few pages if it had come from an unknown instead of a guy with a big fan club who would have bought the phone book if it had had his name on it.

But here. Have a rat.
